πάντων. Every particle of matter is in continual movement. All things are in flux like the waters of a river. One thing alone is per· manent, the universal law which reveals itself in this movement. This is Zeus, the all-pervading reason of the world. Itis only the illusion cf the senses which makes us fancy that there are such things as permanent substances. Fire exhibita most clearly the incessant movement and activity cf the world: confined in the body it con· stitutes the human soul, in the universe at large it is God (the substance and the process being thus identified).

Heraclitus is the first philosopher of whom we read that he referred to the doctrines of other philosophers. He is said to have spoken highly of some of the seven Wise Men, but condemned severely Pythagoras and Xenophanes as well as the poets Hesiod, Homer and Archilochus. Though I agree with Uebcrweg in classing him with the older Ionics, yet his philosophy was no doubt largely developed with a reference tc the rival schools of Italy.
